That error means exactly what it says: in your `onStageStart` handler you’re **using a variable named `round` that isn’t in scope**. You destructured only `{ stage }`, so `round` is undefined at the JS level (lexical error), not an Empirica runtime thing.

Use the `round` that Empirica passes to the callback:

```js
Empirica.onStageStart(({ game, round, stage }) => {
  const attr = chatV2;
  const roundIndex = Number(round.get(roundIndex) ?? 0); // ✅ now in scope

  for (const p of game.players) {
    // ensure chat vector
    if (!Array.isArray(p.round.get(attr))) p.round.set(attr, []);

    // per-player image (no repeats within player)
    const deck = p.get(image_deck) || [];
    const img = deck[roundIndex % deck.length];
    p.round.set(image, img);

    // stable avatar for this player
    const avatarPath = p.get(avatar_url) || toPublicPath(img);

    // kickoff message once per round
    const msgs = p.round.get(attr) || [];
    const already = msgs.some(m => m && m.tag === kickoff && m.for === p.id);

    const order = p.get(greetings_order) || greetings;
    const text = order[roundIndex] ?? Hi!;

    if (!already) {
      p.round.append(attr, {
        text,
        sender: { id: p.id, name: Other Player, avatar: avatarPath },
        createdAt: Date.now(),
        tag: kickoff,
        for: p.id,
      });
    }
  }
});
```

Notes:

- You **can** also do `const roundIndex = Number(stage.currentRound.get(roundIndex) ?? 0);` if your Empirica version exposes `stage.currentRound`, but the canonical, least-surprising way is to just destructure `{ round }` from the callback args.
- The `ReferenceError` would not occur if `round` existed but was `undefined`; you’d get a different failure later. This specific error only happens because `round` wasn’t declared in that scope.

