You’re right that **`onGameStart` can see `game.players`**—you can initialize any players that are already attached *at that moment*. What bites you is:

1) **Not all eventual players are guaranteed to be present yet.** Late joiners won’t be in `game.players` when `onGameStart` fires, so they’ll miss your per-player `p.set(...)`.
2) **`p.round` does not exist in `onGameStart`.** Player-Round scope is created when the round actually starts. So anything that reads/writes `p.round.*` must happen at/after `round.start` / `stage.start`.

So the safe pattern is: **initialize whoever is present in `onGameStart`, and also initialize any late joiners the first time you see them** (e.g., `onPlayerCreated` if available, or lazily at the start of their first round/stage).

